[[ja:й»„ж«Ёжҹ“еҫЎиўҚ]]

{{Double image aside|right|Emperor Naruhito (cropped).jpg |209| Emperor Akihito 199011 1.jpg |214|Left: [[2019]] (Reiwa 1), Emperor [[Naruhito]] wearing the KЕҚrozen no GohЕҚ<br>Right: [[1990]] (Heisei 2), Emperor [[Akihito]] wearing the same ceremonial robe during his reign.}}
'''KЕҚrozen no GohЕҚ''' (й»„ж«Ёжҹ“еҫЎиўҚ) is a {{ill|sokutai|ja|жқҹеёҜ}} ceremonial robe worn exclusively by the [[Emperor of Japan]] during enthronement ceremonies and important rituals. It is a highly symbolic robe, dyed in the unique color known as {{ill|KЕҚrozen|ja|й»„ж«Ёжҹ“}}, reserved solely for the Emperor.

The color kЕҚrozen is derived from natural dyes, specifically the bark of the {{ill|Yamahaze|ja|еұұж«Ё}} tree and the heartwood of {{ill|Sappanwood|ja|иҳҮиҠі}}. It has been described as a "reddish-yellow"{{Sfn|ж—Ҙжң¬еӣҪиӘһеӨ§иҫһе…ё|2000}} or "yellowish-brown."{{Sfn|й«ҳз”°|1986}} Variations in tone are said to reflect differences in era and the wearer's age.{{Sfn|йҲҙжңЁ|1985}} In 2019, during the [[:en:2019_Japanese_imperial_transition#Enthronement_Ceremony|Sokutai Ceremony]], foreign media described the color as "brown-gold." <ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-50120563 'Naruhito: Japan's emperor proclaims enthronement in ancient ceremony'], BBC, October 22, 2019.</ref>

== History and Origin ==

The origins of the KЕҚrozen no GohЕҚ trace back to the [[Heian period]]. Initially formalized by Emperor [[Saga]] in {{ill|820|ja|ејҳд»Ғ11е№ҙ}}, the robe's use for specific court rituals and interactions was outlined in the imperial decree recorded in the {{ill|Nihon Kiryaku|ja|ж—Ҙжң¬зҙҖз•Ҙ}}. Before this, clothing regulations for emperors were not explicitly stated in earlier codes, such as the {{ill|YЕҚrЕҚ Code|ja|йӨҠиҖҒеҫӢд»Ө}}.{{Sfn|й»’еқӮ|1939|p=213}}

KЕҚrozen's color was inspired by {{ill|Tang Dynasty|ja|е”җ}} culture but adapted uniquely in Japan. Unlike the {{ill|Zhehuangpao|zh|иөӯй»„иўҚ}} worn by Tang emperors, kЕҚrozen is associated with the radiant midday sun.{{sfn|й«ҳз”°|1986}} This association is detailed in later writings, such as Takakura NagatsuneвҖҷs ''ZokushinsЕҚ HishЕҚ'' (1288), which states, "The color of the sun is befitting for the Emperor."{{sfn|жӯҰз”°|жҙҘз”°|2016|p=166}} 

Since the establishment of the robe's exclusive use for emperors, kЕҚrozen has been regarded as a {{ill|forbidden color|ja|зҰҒиүІ}}вҖ”strictly prohibited for use by anyone else.{{sfn|й«ҳз”°|1986}}

== Design and Construction ==

=== Dyeing Process ===
According to the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|е»¶е–ңејҸ}}, dyeing the kЕҚrozen fabric required a precise mixture of yamahaze bark and sappanwood. The result was a rich, subdued yellow-brown color, symbolizing the dignity of the Emperor. Due to the complexity of the process, achieving a consistent hue was challenging, even for skilled dyers.{{sfn|еҗүеІЎ|2000}}

=== Patterns and Textures ===
The robe's patterns have evolved. Initially, designs such as ''Kiritake HЕҚЕҚmon'' (paulownia, bamboo, and phoenix motifs) were used. By the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|е®Өз”әжҷӮд»Ј}}, the design transitioned to rectangular ''kakugata mon'' patterns incorporating mythical creatures like the phoenix and kirin.{{sfn|йҲҙжңЁ|1985}} These patterns remain in use today.

=== Fabric and Lining ===
Modern KЕҚrozen no GohЕҚ robes are made with ''koteaya'' fabric, and their linings vary by tradition.{{sfn|й«ҳз”°|1986}}

== Ritual and Usage ==
The robe is integral to imperial rituals, including the {{ill|Enthronement of the Japanese emperor|ja|еҚідҪҚзӨјжӯЈж®ҝгҒ®е„Җ}}, {{ill|Shihohai|lt=Ritual of the Four Directions|ja|еӣӣж–№жӢқ}}, and other key {{ill|Imperial Household Shinto|ja|е®®дёӯзҘӯзҘҖ}} ceremonies. Exceptions include the {{ill|Niinamesai|ja|ж–°еҳ—зҘӯ}}, where the Emperor wears a ceremonial white robe (''gosai fuku'').

