The color kЕҚrozen is derived from natural dyes, specifically the bark of the {{ill|Yamahaze|ja|еұұж«Ё|12=draft}} tree and the heartwood of {{ill|Sappanwood|ja|иҳҮиҠі|12=draft}}. It has been described as a "reddish-yellow"{{Sfn|ж—Ҙжң¬еӣҪиӘһеӨ§иҫһе…ё|2000}} or "yellowish-brown."{{Sfn|й«ҳз”°|1986}} Variations in tone are said to reflect differences in era and the wearer's age.{{Sfn|йҲҙжңЁ|1985}} In 2019, during the [[:en:2019_Japanese_imperial_transition#Enthronement_Ceremony|Sokutai Ceremony]], foreign media described the color as "brown-gold." <ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-50120563 'Naruhito: Japan's emperor proclaims enthronement in ancient ceremony'], BBC, October 22, 2019.</ref>
== History and Origin ==
The origins of the KЕҚrozen no GohЕҚ trace back to the [[Heian period]]. Initially formalized by Emperor [[Saga]] in {{ill|820|ja|ејҳд»Ғ11th year|12=draft}}, the robe's use for specific court rituals and interactions was outlined in the imperial decree recorded in the {{ill|Nihon Kiryaku|ja|ж—Ҙжң¬зҙҖз•Ҙ|12=draft}}. Before this, clothing regulations for emperors were not explicitly stated in earlier codes, such as the {{ill|YЕҚrЕҚ Code|ja|йӨҠиҖҒеҫӢд»Ө|12=draft}}.{{Sfn|й»’еқӮ|1939|p=213}}
KЕҚrozen's color was inspired by {{ill|Tang Dynasty|ja|е”җ|12=draft}} culture but adapted uniquely in Japan. Unlike the {{ill|Zhehuangpao|zh|иөӯй»„иўҚ|12=draft}} worn by Tang emperors, kЕҚrozen is associated with the radiant midday sun.{{sfn|й«ҳз”°|1986}} This association is detailed in later writings, such as Takakura NagatsuneвҖҷs ''ZokushinsЕҚ HishЕҚ'' (1288), which states, "The color of the sun is befitting for the Emperor."{{sfn|жӯҰз”°|жҙҘз”°|2016|p=166}}
Since the establishment of the robe's exclusive use for emperors, kЕҚrozen has been regarded as a {{ill|forbidden color|ja|зҰҒиүІ|12=draft}}вҖ”strictly prohibited for use by anyone else.{{sfn|й«ҳз”°|1986}}
== Design and Construction ==
=== Dyeing Process === According to the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|е»¶е–ңејҸ|12=draft}}, dyeing the kЕҚrozen fabric required a precise mixture of yamahaze bark and sappanwood. The result was a rich, subdued yellow-brown color, symbolizing the dignity of the Emperor. Due to the complexity of the process, achieving a consistent hue was challenging, even for skilled dyers.{{sfn|еҗүеІЎ|2000}}
=== Patterns and Textures === The robe's patterns have evolved. Initially, designs such as ''Kiritake HЕҚЕҚmon'' (paulownia, bamboo, and phoenix motifs) were used. By the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|е®Өз”әжҷӮд»Ј|12=draft}}, the design transitioned to rectangular ''kakugata mon'' patterns incorporating mythical creatures like the phoenix and kirin.{{sfn|йҲҙжңЁ|1985}} These patterns remain in use today.
=== Fabric and Lining === Modern KЕҚrozen no GohЕҚ robes are made with ''koteaya'' fabric, and their linings vary by tradition.{{sfn|й«ҳз”°|1986}}
== Ritual and Usage == The robe is integral to imperial rituals, including the {{ill|Enthronement of the Japanese emperor|ja|еҚідҪҚзӨјжӯЈж®ҝгҒ®е„Җ|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shihohai|lt=Ritual of the Four Directions|ja|еӣӣж–№жӢқ|12=draft}}, and other key {{ill|Imperial Household Shinto|ja|е®®дёӯзҘӯзҘҖ|12=draft}} ceremonies. Exceptions include the {{ill|Niinamesai|ja|ж–°еҳ—зҘӯ|12=draft}}, where the Emperor wears a ceremonial white robe (''gosai fuku'').
== Gallery == <gallery> File:Emperor Showa.jpg|[[1928]] (ShЕҚwa 3), Emperor [[ShЕҚwa]] wearing the KЕҚrozen no GohЕҚ during his enthronement ceremony. File:Ceremony of the Enthronement of His Majesty the Emperor at the Seiden7.jpg|2019 (Reiwa 1), Emperor Naruhito during the ''Sokutai Ceremony.'' File:Rittaishi of Prince Naruhito.jpg|Crown Prince Naruhito's investiture ceremony. File:Emperor Takakura.jpg|Portrait of [[Emperor Takakura]], depicted in a KЕҚrozen robe. File:Tang Emperor Taizong.jpg|Tang Emperor Taizong wearing a robe similar in color to KЕҚrozen. </gallery>
